SIMPLE: exculpate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exculpate
<hw>Ex*cul"pate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Exculpated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ets>p. pr. & vb.
n.</ets>. <conjf>Exculpating</conjf> (<?/).]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>culpatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>culpare</ets> to
find fault with, to blame, <ets>culpa</ets> fault. See
<er>Culpable</er>.]</ety> <def>To clear from alleged fault or guilt; to
prove to be guiltless; to relieve of blame; to acquit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>exculpated</qex> himself from being the author of the
heroic epistle.</q> <rj><qau>Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>exculpate</qex> him further for his writing against me.</q>
<rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To exonerate; absolve; clear; acquit; excuse;
vindicate; justify.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>exculpated</ent>⟦br⟧
